'''Christian Sommerfeldt''' (6 January 1746 – 30 May 1811) was a Norwegian geographer and civil servant.
==Personal life== He was born at Sukkestad in [[Østre Toten|Toten]] as a son of district stipendiary magistrate and chancellor councillor David Christian Sommerfelt (1717–1773) and Benedicte "Bente" Christine Hoff.<ref name=nbl>{{cite encyclopedia|year=|title=Christian Sommerfelt|encyclopedia=[[Norsk biografisk leksikon]]|first=Arnfinn|last=Engen|volume=|editor=[[Knut Helle|Helle, Knut]]|publisher=Kunnskapsforlaget|location=Oslo|url=http://www.snl.no/.nbl_biografi/Christian_Sommerfelt/utdypning|language=Norwegian|accessdate=20 June 2012}}</ref> His grandfather Christian Sommerfelt was also district stipendiary magistrate. His great-grandfather and uncle were both named Hans, and became priests. The latter worked in Denmark and became ancestor for a Danish family line. Christian Sommerfeldt became ancestor of a Norwegian branch of Sommerfeldts, and so did his brother [[Ole Hannibal Sommerfeldt|Ole Hannibal]].<ref name=snl>{{cite encyclopedia|year=|title=Sommerfeldt|encyclopedia=[[Store norske leksikon]]|editor=|publisher=|location=|url=http://www.snl.no/Sommerfeldt|language=Norwegian|accessdate=20 June 2012}}</ref> Through his sister Maria he was an uncle of [[Lauritz Weidemann]].<ref name=nbl-lw>{{cite encyclopedia |title=Lauritz Weidemann |encyclopedia=[[Norsk biografisk leksikon]]|first=Gustav |last=Sætra |editor=[[Knut Helle|Helle, Knut]] |publisher=Kunnskapsforlaget |location=Oslo|url=http://www.snl.no/.nbl_biografi/Lauritz_Weidemann/utdypning |language=Norwegian|accessdate=9 July 2012}}</ref>
Christian Sommerfeldt was married twice. First he married vicar's daughter Karen Magdalena Mandahl (1764–1791) in March 1784 in [[Land, Norway|Land]]. After her death, in May 1793 in [[Oslo|Christiania]] he married stipendiary magistrate's daughter Anna Sophia Hagerup (1775–1821).<ref name=nbl/> Their son [[Søren Christian Sommerfelt]] was a priest and botanist.<ref name=nbl/>
==Career== Sommerfeldt grew up at Sukkestad, and enrolled at the [[University of Copenhagen]] at the age of thirteen. He finished his theological studies at the age of twenty before studying geography and history at [[Sorø Academy]]. In 1776 he published the two textbooks ''Geographie til Ungdommens Brug'' and ''Kort Udtog af Geographien til Begynderes Bedste'', which both came in six editions. He was offered to succeed [[Gerhard Schøning]] as professor in these subjects, but instead shifted his academic field again, to practical agriculture and national economy.<ref name=nbl/>
In 1776 he entered the Danish civil service. In 1779 he was promoted to chamber councillor ({{lang-da|Kammerråd}}). In 1781 he was appointed as [[List of County Governors of Oppland|County Governor of Christians Amt]], which he remained until his death in 1811.<ref name=nbl/> He resided at Sukkestad. In his position, he continued his endeavor for improving practical agriculture, forestry, and other rural enterprise in [[Oppland|Christians Amt]]. He collected data from his county, and based on this data he published ''Efterretninger angaaende Christians amt'' in 1790. After the [[topography|topographical]] society ''Topographisk Selskab for Norge'' was published in 1791 and started the journal ''Topographisk Journal for Norge'', his text was reprinted there.<ref name=nbl/>
